{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":610,"record_hash":"sha256:45822c769fb022af5c8b1eb82c4ba66923502c0bdbdf6d10f9e548599ce6302f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:53:04.409Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"Yes, the split basically fits. Keep it. But the current `TurnSummary` is too skinny for the reads you care about.\\n\\n**What Fits**\\n- `TurnDetail` as the source of truth is right: record membership plus environment snapshot belongs there.\\n- Derived branch/review/change indexes are the right answer for review sharing. They make lookup cheap without pretending association is truth.\\n- Keeping transcript ownership at session level is still the correct call. Branches/PRs should discover or reference sessions, not own records.\\n\\n**What’s Missing**\\n- `TurnSummary` needs enough to support fast handoff timelines without opening every detail:\\n  `{ turn_key, captured_at, record_count, previous_turn_key, environment_snapshot_status, source_key, first_record_index, last_record_index }`\\n- If summaries are not strictly nested under one session key, add `session_key` too.\\n- Add index metadata: schema/version, key canonicalization rules, and rebuild/invalidation behavior.\\n- Add an explicit future relationship shape separate from indexes, e.g. confirmed target-to-session with optional turn scope. Indexes are evidence lookup, not product truth.\\n- Add privacy/publication language for review sharing. Environment snapshots include branch names, paths, PR ids, commit ids. Fine repo-scoped, risky in shared web views.\\n\\n**What To Move**\\n- Keep `record_count` and snapshot status in summary.\\n- Keep full record membership and full environment only in detail.\\n- Put `source_key` in summary. The `turn_key` is opaque, and source matters for debugging/order/rendering.\\n- Do not put observed branches/reviews/changes in summary. Those belong in detail plus derived indexes.\\n- Keep `previous_turn_key` in summary; optionally duplicate in detail only if details should be self-contained export objects.\\n\\n**Main Risks**\\n- Atomicity: transcript writes succeeding while turn writes fail creates orphaned records. Needs a repair path or one logical GitMeta update.\\n- First backfill turns can be huge and misleading as “one turn.” The model says this, but UI must label it as capture observation, not native conversation turn.\\n- Indexes will rot unless rebuild semantics are boring and explicit.\\n- Branch-name indexes are weak in GitButler multi-branch worktrees. Useful candidate lookup, bad association truth.\\n- Review sharing needs confidence/reason display. Otherwise reviewers may overread “seen near this PR” as “this session produced this PR.”\\n\\nVerdict: good architecture. Thicken `TurnSummary` slightly, keep `TurnDetail` authoritative, treat indexes as disposable acceleration, and draw a hard line between evidence and confirmed association.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:53:04.409Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}